posts.raw_content:
I work for the largest Heavy Diesel Emissions Shop in the US as in 18 Wheelers.  The Diesel Emissions Industry as a whole normally slows down for a few weeks in the Spring and Fall.   This year it started mid summer and has only gotten worse.  


My job requires I visit every Diesel Truck and Trailer Repair Shop in the Tri State area including most of Pennsylvania, Delaware and New Jersey.   The leading topic of conversation in every shop is Why is it so slow?  Keep in mind this is the very tip of the economy.  Anything that happens up here trickles downstream in short order.

Every shop looking to hire Diesel Mechanics in July is laying off.  This is unheard of.  Diesel Mechanics are worth their weight in gold. 

Point is when trucking isn't moving neither is money.   Guys doing this much longer than I are saying they've never seen it this slow before.  Take this as a potential heads up, a factor to consider in your planning.  Is the economy collapsing?  I have no idea but seeing Diesel Mechanics being laid off is biblical in its severity.   Heads up Pedes.  Prepare Accordingly
